definition: "Progesterone is a steroid hormone produced primarily by the corpus luteum (the temporary endocrine structure that forms from the ovarian follicle after ovulation) and, during pregnancy, by the placenta. In premenopausal women, progesterone is secreted in the second half of the menstrual cycle (the luteal phase) following ovulation, rising sharply after ovulation and falling if pregnancy does not occur. In men, progesterone is produced in small quantities by the adrenal glands and testes, where it serves as a precursor to testosterone and other steroid hormones. Progesterone acts through progesterone receptors found throughout the body — in the uterus, brain, breast tissue, cardiovascular system, and bone — making its effects systemic rather than purely reproductive. It is also the direct precursor to cortisol, aldosterone, and the neurosteroid allopregnanolone, which modulates GABA-A receptors in the brain and is a primary mediator of progesterone's calming and sleep-promoting effects."
why_it_matters: "Progesterone is typically the first major reproductive hormone to decline in perimenopause — often beginning in a woman's late 30s or early 40s, years before estrogen falls and before periods become irregular. This early progesterone decline produces a clinical syndrome that is widely experienced but rarely attributed to its actual cause: worsening sleep quality (particularly sleep maintenance insomnia), increased anxiety and irritability, heavier and more irregular periods, and worsening PMS. Because estrogen remains relatively normal during early perimenopause while progesterone drops, estrogen's effects become relatively dominant — a state called estrogen dominance — producing bloating, breast tenderness, and mood instability. Beyond its reproductive roles, progesterone has important neuroprotective, anti-inflammatory, and cardiovascular effects. In men, progesterone serves as a precursor in the testosterone synthesis pathway and has direct effects on sleep quality and mood through allopregnanolone — though its clinical relevance in male longevity medicine is less studied than in women."

